<subSubSection id="C36F650CFFD4FFDFFCF2FE131532C006" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="701" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCA3687FFD4FFD8FCF2FE1314E1C2EA" blockId="3.[826,1442,413,1903]" box="[826,938,413,434]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">
<emphasis id="B901EA95FFD4FFD8FCF2FE1314E1C2EA" box="[826,938,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA3687FFD4FFDFFCF2FE3515B9C2CB" blockId="3.[826,1442,413,1903]" lastBlockId="4.[144,759,198,403]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="701" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">
<emphasis id="B901EA95FFD4FFD8FCF2FE3514CEC288" box="[826,901,443,464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Larva:</emphasis>
Length, 
<quantity id="4C8D9B62FFD4FFD8FC24FE34131DC288" box="[1004,1110,442,464]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="0.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" unit="mm" value="27.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="4.0">4–50 mm</quantity>
long; subcylindrical in crosssection; truncate anteriorly, usually tapering posteriorly because of narrowing of the anal segment (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FC8AFD981489C175" box="[834,962,534,557]" captionStart-0="Figures 20–22" captionStart-1="Figures 23–24" captionStart-2="Figures 25–27" captionStartId-0="41.[164,254,829,848]" captionStartId-1="41.[164,254,1432,1451]" captionStartId-2="42.[144,234,1609,1630]" captionTargetBox-0="[421,1184,197,797]" captionTargetBox-1="[421,1185,926,1401]" captionTargetBox-2="[146,1852,426,1576]" captionTargetId-0="figure-0@41.[419,1187,195,799]" captionTargetId-1="figure-33@41.[419,1187,924,1403]" captionTargetId-2="figure-0@42.[144,1856,421,1580]" captionTargetPageId-0="41" captionTargetPageId-1="41" captionTargetPageId-2="42" captionText-0="Figures 20–22. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 6 mm. 20, Copestylum satur; 21, Copestylum tetetzoi sp. nov.; 22, Copestylum vittatum." captionText-1="Figures 23–24. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 6 mm. 23, Copestylum haagii; 24, Copestylum hoya." captionText-2="Figures 25–27. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 7 mm. 25. Copestylum apiciferum; 26, Copestylum isabellina; 27, Copestylum sica." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443492" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443494" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443496" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5443492/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5443494/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5443496/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 20–27</figureCitation>
). Mouthparts saprophagous i.e. mandibles and mandibular lobes inverted into the oral cavity, attached to the pseudocephalon and forming a filter (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B76FFD4FFD8FC48FDFC1356C1D0" author="Hartley JC" box="[896,1053,626,648]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" pagination="261 - 280" refId="ref33425" refString="Hartley JC. 1963. The cephalopharyngeal apparatus of syrphid larvae and its relationship to other Diptera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 141: 261 - 280." type="journal article" year="1963">Hartley, 1963</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B76FFD4FFD8FBE0FDFC1207C1D0" author="Rotheray GE &amp; Gilbert F" box="[1064,1356,626,648]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" pagination="287 - 323" refId="ref33826" refString="Rotheray GE, Gilbert F. 2008. Phylogenetic relationships and the larval head of the lower Cyclorrhapha (Diptera). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 153: 287 - 323." type="journal article" year="2008">Rotheray &amp; Gilbert, 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Cephapharyngeal head skeleton varying in relative lengths of the dorsal and ventral cornua and sclerotization of the vertical plate (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FBDEFD4013DDC1BC" box="[1046,1174,718,740]" captionStart-0="Figures 35–40" captionStart-1="Figures 41–43" captionStartId-0="44.[144,234,1119,1138]" captionStartId-1="45.[164,254,1494,1513]" captionTargetBox-0="[367,1198,200,1089]" captionTargetBox-1="[494,1113,196,1461]" captionTargetId-0="figure-0@44.[367,1201,197,1089]" captionTargetId-1="figure-0@45.[494,1113,194,1464]" captionTargetPageId-0="44" captionTargetPageId-1="45" captionText-0="Figures 35–40. Third stage larval Copestylum, head skeleton, apex to the left, scale bar = 1.4 mm. 35, Copestylum hambletoni; 36, Copestylum vittatum; 37, Copestylum fraudulentum; 38, Copestylum marginatum; 39, Copestylum haagii, 39A, whole head skeleton; 39B, grinding mill, ventral view; 40, Copestylum hoya." captionText-1="Figures 41–43. Third stage larval Copestylum, head skeleton, apex to the left, scale bar = 1.4 mm. 41, Copestylum dispar; 42, Copestylum apiciferum; 43, Copestylum latum." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443500" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443502" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5443500/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5443502/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 35–43</figureCitation>
). Dorsal cornua generally rounded apically and only slightly inclined backwards, always shorter than ventral cornua. Mandibles and mandibular lobes variable in size. Dorsal bridge present. Ventral cornu with or without dorsal apodeme (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FBC3FCE913D9C025" box="[1035,1170,871,893]" captionStart="Figures 41–43" captionStartId="45.[164,254,1494,1513]" captionTargetBox="[494,1113,196,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-0@45.[494,1113,194,1464]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figures 41–43. Third stage larval Copestylum, head skeleton, apex to the left, scale bar = 1.4 mm. 41, Copestylum dispar; 42, Copestylum apiciferum; 43, Copestylum latum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443502/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 42, 43</figureCitation>
). Pharyngeal grinding mill consisting of two opposable sclerotized plates (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B76FFD4FFD8FC8AFC2A14A9C0E2" author="Hartley JC" box="[834,994,932,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" pagination="261 - 280" refId="ref33425" refString="Hartley JC. 1963. The cephalopharyngeal apparatus of syrphid larvae and its relationship to other Diptera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 141: 261 - 280." type="journal article" year="1963">Hartley, 1963</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B76FFD4FFD8FC3AFC2A13D8C0E2" author="Roberts MJ" box="[1010,1171,932,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700" pagination="279 - 284" refId="ref33744" refString="Roberts MJ. 1969. Pharyngeal grinding mills in some Diptera larvae. The Entomologist 102: 279 - 284." type="journal article" year="1969">Roberts, 1969</bibRefCitation>
) sometimes present at the distal apex of the ventral cornua (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FAD8FC4D122DC080" box="[1296,1382,963,985]" captionStart="Figures 35–40" captionStartId="44.[144,234,1119,1138]" captionTargetBox="[367,1198,200,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-0@44.[367,1201,197,1089]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="Figures 35–40. Third stage larval Copestylum, head skeleton, apex to the left, scale bar = 1.4 mm. 35, Copestylum hambletoni; 36, Copestylum vittatum; 37, Copestylum fraudulentum; 38, Copestylum marginatum; 39, Copestylum haagii, 39A, whole head skeleton; 39B, grinding mill, ventral view; 40, Copestylum hoya." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443500/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 39</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FABFFC4D12DEC081" box="[1399,1429,963,985]" captionStart="Figures 41–43" captionStartId="45.[164,254,1494,1513]" captionTargetBox="[494,1113,196,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-0@45.[494,1113,194,1464]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figures 41–43. Third stage larval Copestylum, head skeleton, apex to the left, scale bar = 1.4 mm. 41, Copestylum dispar; 42, Copestylum apiciferum; 43, Copestylum latum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443502/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">43</figureCitation>
). Prothorax with well-developed lateral lips and anterior fold. Anterior fold coated in transverse rows of backwardly directed spicules (sclerotised setae). Thorax with varying arrangements and 
<typeStatus id="54CE8825FFD4FFD8FACEFBB01208C70B" box="[1286,1347,1086,1107]" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">types</typeStatus>
of setae and spicules (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FC2AFBD2132AC729" box="[994,1121,1116,1138]" captionStart="Figures 28–34" captionStartId="43.[164,254,1523,1542]" captionTargetBox="[496,1111,193,1490]" captionTargetId="figure-0@43.[494,1113,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 28–34. Third stage larval Copestylum, body vestiture, black areas represent extent of sclerotization; scale bar = 1 mm. 28, 31, and 34, Copestylum quadratum, 28, long fine setae from the dorsum of the metathorax; 31, crochets from proleg on first abdominal segment, larger crochet = primary; smaller crochet = secondary; 34, branched setae from base of lateral lips; 29–30, Copestylum isabellina, 29, short, broad setae from the dorsum of the metathorax, 30, spicules from the anterior fold of the prothorax; 32, Copestylum hambletoni, broad based setae from dorsum of mesothorax; 33, Copestylum multipunctatum sp. nov., triangular shaped setae from dorsum of the anal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443498" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443498/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 28–34</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FBBBFBD213D9C72A" box="[1139,1170,1116,1138]" captionStart="Figures 54–57" captionStartId="48.[144,234,1180,1199]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1148]" captionTargetId="figure-0@48.[303,1263,195,1150]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figures 54–57. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images, 54, Copestylum pictum, dorsum of prothoracic shield length 3.5 mm; 55, Copestylum spinigera, pupal spiracles, ventral view length 1.12 mm; 56, 57, Copestylum hambletoni, pupal spiracle length 1.3 mm; 56, ventral view; 57, dorsal view. af, apex of anterior fold with spicules; as, anterior spiracle; lf, longitudinal fold; s, spicule groups on anterodorsal margins of mesothorax and metathorax; P, prothorax; Ms, mesothorax; Mt, metathorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443510/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">54</figureCitation>
). Mesothoracic prolegs present with one to three rows of crochets, rows either transverse or forming ‘U’ or ‘W’ shaped rows. Prolegs on abdominal segments 1–3 or 1–6 with two or three transverse rows of crochets. Abdomen coated in vestiture comprising setae or spicules of various shapes and densities which generally becomes longer towards the anal segment and shorter on the ventral surface. Anal segment divided dorsally into two sections; the anterior section bearing two pairs of lappets (fleshy projections with an apical sensillum and surrounding setae) usually of unequal length and the posterior section bearing a single pair of lappets (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FC8AFA641489C558" box="[834,962,1514,1536]" captionStart-0="Figures 20–22" captionStart-1="Figures 23–24" captionStart-2="Figures 25–27" captionStartId-0="41.[164,254,829,848]" captionStartId-1="41.[164,254,1432,1451]" captionStartId-2="42.[144,234,1609,1630]" captionTargetBox-0="[421,1184,197,797]" captionTargetBox-1="[421,1185,926,1401]" captionTargetBox-2="[146,1852,426,1576]" captionTargetId-0="figure-0@41.[419,1187,195,799]" captionTargetId-1="figure-33@41.[419,1187,924,1403]" captionTargetId-2="figure-0@42.[144,1856,421,1580]" captionTargetPageId-0="41" captionTargetPageId-1="41" captionTargetPageId-2="42" captionText-0="Figures 20–22. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 6 mm. 20, Copestylum satur; 21, Copestylum tetetzoi sp. nov.; 22, Copestylum vittatum." captionText-1="Figures 23–24. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 6 mm. 23, Copestylum haagii; 24, Copestylum hoya." captionText-2="Figures 25–27. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 7 mm. 25. Copestylum apiciferum; 26, Copestylum isabellina; 27, Copestylum sica." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443492" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443494" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443496" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5443492/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5443494/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5443496/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 20–27</figureCitation>
). Base of first (anterodorsal) pair of lappets with an additional short, sometimes inconspicuous fleshy projection bearing an apical sensillum and surrounding setae. Anal segment elongate, longer than sixth abdominal segment, or contracted, shorter than sixth abdominal segment. Posterior breathing tubes fused into a single sclerotized structure variable in length and ornamentation (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FB52F94E1250C58E" box="[1178,1307,1728,1750]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 44, 46</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FAE0F94E123BC58E" box="[1320,1392,1728,1750]" captionStart="Figures 58–61" captionStartId="49.[164,254,1145,1164]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-0@49.[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figures 58–61. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images, 58, 59, Copestylum spinigera; 58, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.87 mm; 59, prp, apical view width = 0.8 mm; 60, Copestylum cockerelli, prp dorsal view width at TR = 1.5 mm; 61, Copestylum hambletoni, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.45 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443512/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">60, 61</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FAB7F94E1412C5AC" captionStart="Figures 68–73" captionStartId="51.[164,254,1558,1577]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-0@51.[323,1283,195,1528]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="Figures 68–73. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images. 68, 70, Copestylum macrocephalum; 68, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width of TR = 1.3 mm; 70, prp, apical; 71, Copestylum posticum; pupal spiracles, dorsal view length = 0.93 mm; 69, 72–73, Copestylum isabellina; 69, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.1 mm, 72, pupal spiracles, ventrolateral view length 0.82 mm; 73, spiracular openings, apical and lateral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443518/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">68, 70</figureCitation>
). Close to the apex of the breathing tube a shallow to deep transverse ridge (TR) (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FB7AF9731243C44A" box="[1202,1288,1789,1811]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">Figs 44</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD4FFD8FAD1F97312DFC44B" box="[1305,1428,1789,1811]" captionStart="Figures 58–61" captionStartId="49.[164,254,1145,1164]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-0@49.[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figures 58–61. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images, 58, 59, Copestylum spinigera; 58, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.87 mm; 59, prp, apical view width = 0.8 mm; 60, Copestylum cockerelli, prp dorsal view width at TR = 1.5 mm; 61, Copestylum hambletoni, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.45 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443512/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="700">58, 60, 61</figureCitation>
), section of breathing tube above TR to apex (AP) always with a different surface ornamentation than below: TR from smooth and shiny to being punctured. Spiracular plates usually level each with three pairs of curved to convoluted openings and four groups of interspiracular setae, setae often missing (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD3FFDFFDBBFE8D1582C241" box="[627,713,259,281]" captionStart="Figures 58–61" captionStartId="49.[164,254,1145,1164]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-0@49.[323,1283,195,1115]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figures 58–61. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images, 58, 59, Copestylum spinigera; 58, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.87 mm; 59, prp, apical view width = 0.8 mm; 60, Copestylum cockerelli, prp dorsal view width at TR = 1.5 mm; 61, Copestylum hambletoni, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.45 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443512/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Figs 59</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD3FFDFFD1CFE8D15B9C241" box="[724,754,259,281]" captionStart="Figures 62–65" captionStartId="50.[144,234,1071,1090]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,196,1038]" captionTargetId="figure-0@50.[303,1263,196,1041]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figures 62–65. Puparium of Copestylum dispar, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images. 62, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 1.0 mm; 63, prp, apical view width = 0.9 mm; 64, pupal spiracle, ventral view length 1.12 mm; 65, pupal spiracle, dorsolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443514" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443514/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">63</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD3FFDFFF58FEAC17E4C260" box="[144,175,290,312]" captionStart="Figures 68–73" captionStartId="51.[164,254,1558,1577]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-0@51.[323,1283,195,1528]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="Figures 68–73. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images. 68, 70, Copestylum macrocephalum; 68, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width of TR = 1.3 mm; 70, prp, apical; 71, Copestylum posticum; pupal spiracles, dorsal view length = 0.93 mm; 69, 72–73, Copestylum isabellina; 69, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.1 mm, 72, pupal spiracles, ventrolateral view length 0.82 mm; 73, spiracular openings, apical and lateral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443518/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">70</figureCitation>
). Pupal breathing tubes variable in length, shape, ornamentation, and arrangement of spiracular openings, with openings almost reaching base, concentrated at the apex or on the underside (
<figureCitation id="134E2A02FFD3FFDFFDAEFEF315ACC2CB" box="[614,743,381,403]" captionStart-0="Figures 44–47" captionStart-1="Figures 48–53" captionStartId-0="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionStartId-1="47.[164,254,1555,1574]" captionTargetBox-0="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetBox-1="[323,1283,195,1523]" captionTargetId-0="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId-1="figure-0@47.[323,1283,195,1525]" captionTargetPageId-0="46" captionTargetPageId-1="47" captionText-0="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." captionText-1="Figures 48–53. Pupal spiracles of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 48, 50, Copestylum fornax; 48, dorsolateral view length 0.38 mm; 50, whole view from above scale as indicated; 49, Copestylum satur, lateral view length 0.73 mm; 51, 53, Copestylum marginatum; 51, dorsolateral view length 0.82 mm; 53, sculpture between openings, view from above; 52, Copestylum limbipenne, sculpture between openings, view from above." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443508" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5443508/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Figs 47–53</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA3687FFD3FFDFFF58FE541532C006" blockId="4.[144,759,473,863]" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">
<emphasis id="B901EA95FFD3FFDFFF58FE54161DC2B7" box="[144,342,474,495]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
Characters that distinguish larval 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D04FFD3FFDFFF58FE761643C156" baseAuthorityName="Rondani" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[144,264,504,526]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="701" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Volucellini">Volucellini</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D04FFD3FFDFFE42FE761545C155" box="[394,526,504,525]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="701" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EA95FFD3FFDFFE42FE761545C155" box="[394,526,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Copestylum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from other syrphid larvae are the presence of inverted mouthparts and the anal segment divided into two sections with the anterior section bearing two pairs of lappets, the first pair of which has an additional lateral sensillum. 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D04FFD3FFDFFF58FD1F165FC1FE" box="[144,276,657,678]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="701" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EA95FFD3FFDFFF58FD1F165FC1FE" box="[144,276,657,678]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Copestylum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae may be separated from other volucellines by the first two pairs of lappets, which are unequal in length. Rarely are these lappets equal in length but if so, then the lappets are smooth and lack a coating of setae. The 42 species reared from agaves and cacti in this study divide into ten morphological groups (
<tableCitation id="C6F7033CFFD3FFDFFF26FCC6160BC007" box="[238,320,840,863]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[164,228,200,219]" captionText="Table 1. Species groups, constituent species and breeding sites of Copestylum reared in this study" pageId="4" pageNumber="701">Table 1</tableCitation>
) and are diagnosed below.
</paragraph>
